**10/15 SCONE Lecture:**

**Threat Model for Running a Container on the Cloud** :

- The adversary can
  - Read Memory
  - Read/Write Files
  - Read/Drop/Reorder Network Packets
  - Read CPU State (registers, interrupts etc.) -\&gt; this is hard to weaponize

**Secure Guard Extensions (SGX)**

- Given CPU, DRAM, and Enclave
- On the DRAM you have the Enclave Protected Memory (EPC)
  - The CPU cannot access the EPC because there is no translation in the MMU from the CPU to the EPC physical address
- Enclave Protected Memory
  - Encrypted Memory
  - Not accessible by CPU
  - When DRAM is reading it is in protected state, so it is encrypted
- Enclave
  - Encrypted before it leaves the enclave
  - No system calls
  - CPU is not able to access
  - Runs the ring 3 code
- SCONE is about given the above configuration of hardware how do we run a container on top of it?

**Running the Container inside an Enclave:**

- How do we handle System Calls?
  - Any system calls the application on the container tries to do, scone intercepts and invokes them on the Host OS to guarantee correctness and security
  - Enclave (from Haven Microsoft Paper)
    - In the Enclave run an application and a library OS
    - The library OS talks to the Host OS
  - Enclave Set Up from another paper
    - Enclave runs App and GLibC Shim
      - GLibC SHIM communicates between the application and the host OS to invoke system calls
    - The GLibC SHIM communicates with glibc which communicates with the Host OS
  - Enclave with SCONE
    - Application, glibc, and system calls all run on the enclave
    - The enclave communicates with the host OS to invoke the system call
  - SCONE and Asynchronous System Calls (Inside the Enclave)
    - Container tries to do system call s
    - Scone contains a producer queue and a consumer queue (these are visible to application)
    - S gets added to the producer queue
    - Scone encrypts (and may hash certain values) that are being passed to the system call
    - So Scone transforms the system call to a version that is secure for the outside world to consume
    - Then it passes the encrypted values into the Host OS
    - S gets moved to consumer queue
    - And that returns to the container
    - Overall the Asynchronous System Calls provide a lot of benefits
      - If there are many applications that are doing system calls you can batch all the system calls into one file and run it and cache it (Check on this)
      - You can run system calls that are similar on the same core
      - For SCONE it provides security
    - How does SCONE handle a lot of System Calls?
      - M u-threads
      - N k-threads
      - Remember there are no interrupts
      - So you have and Enclave and a Scone (outside the enclave) and the host OS
      - S is added to the producer queue
      - Then you schedule u1 to run and u2 to run
      - One of the scone threads will pick up S from the producer queue
      - The scone thread will execute the system call
      - Then the scone thread will add s back to the consumer queue
      - The you schedule either u1 or u2 to process the result of s from the consumer queue
      - SCONE acts as a
-  How do we handle File IO?
  - SCONE has the concept of shields
    - This is the mechanism with which the scone changes your file and network IO
  - SCONE can also do Authentication
    - Say you have two versions of the file that is encrypted block by blcok
    - An attacker can create a version 3 which is a copy of version 2 except that the last block is different
    - To prevent this

-
  -
    -
      - You create a Merkle Tree where you the parent node is equal to the hash of the two children nodes where each leaf node is a block from a file (A merkle tree can be made up of multiple files that you are trying to protect)
      - This process is called authentication
      - So for every version you create a Merkle Root
        - The attacker cannot create a correct Merkle Root if they have edited the file
        - If you walk the tree you can see exactly which block of the file has been tampered
- How do we handle Network IO?
  - SCONE just uses TLS so that ll traffic is encrypted before being sent
  - We can&#39;t prevent against side channels or timing attacks
  - SCONE only provides protection against CPU tampering

**10/17 Light VM Lecture:**

**Virtualization vs Containers**

- Virtualization
  - Strong Isolation
  - Heavy Weight
- Containers
  - Light weight
  - Iffy isolation

**LightVM**

- VM that is as fast and efficient as containers
- Fast instantiation, destruction and migration
- Low per instance memory foot print
- High density

**Standard VM: Application on top of Distro**

- Most of the VM is not used especially if you are only running one application

**Unikernel: Single application + minimalistic OS**

- Squish everything together in a single address space and process
- Take Nginx and all its processes and put it into one unikernel
- This is all run in a hypervisor or in a VM
- Every application gets its own unikernel
- Advantage
  - Smaller than the whole VM
- Disadvantage
  - Can&#39;t run on bare HW
  - Not as much guaranteed isolation
  - Restricted OS and languages to run a unikernel (Ocamel)
- Examples (Small and one purpose)
  - Daytime - 480 KB disk, 3.4MB RAM
  - Minipython - 3.52MB disk, 8MB RAM
  - TLS Termination Proxy - 3.58MB disk, 8MB RAM

**Tinyx: Small Linux Distro for Target App**

- Find Dependencies
  - Objdump
  - Dpkg
- Install Applications and Dependencies
  - Overlay File System
  - Clean up
- They have a script that automatically decides what are all the requirements of the application and puts it all in one
- This is a minimal kernel not a unikernel
  - All the security features of an os
  - Isolation is there because running in a different address space
  - Mini version of a kernel
  - Just takes out unnecessary parts of the VM
- Lightweight
  - Kernel 1.5MB (compared to 8MB)
  - Image Size 10-30MB (compared to 1GB)
  - Boot 200ms instead of 2s
- Runs one application, will crash if you do anything else

**VM, Container and Process Creation Times**

- Process
  - Sinusoidal Graph with latency
  - Scalable
- Docker Boot
  - Consistent and constant
  - Scalable
- Debian Create
  - Exponential
  - Not Scalable
- MiniOS Boot
  - Linear
  - Not Scalable
- Tinyx Create
  - Linear
  - Not Scalable
  - Provides isolation properties but within the ball park of Docker
- The question is do people care?
  - For VMs people do not care about how long it takes to launch because the expectation is that it will take a long time
  - For containers people do care because they want it to be fast

**A Quick Xen Primer**

- Tinyx identified the problems in Xen and then fixed to make it more efficient
- Xen gives the user utilities to help control the VMs
  - Xl - command line utility to create, migrate, or shutdown a VM
- Must interact with xen store
- Xen IO
  - One part runs in VM and one par runs in Dom0 then Dom0 communicates with the hardware
- Creation Times Breakdown
  - Xen store and garbage collector are biggest reason for time spikes
  - Xen Store
    - Device drivers have watches on Xen Store, then they read Xen Store, then the notify Dom0, then Device Drivers check if  it was created (four steps)
    - More than 30 Xen Store entries are used per device resulting in hundreds of Xen Store accesses

**LightVM Architecture**

- NOXS (no xen store) - replacement for the xen store
  - Xen Store used to
    - Store data
    - Communicate between guests
    - Synchronization
  - NoXS
    - Shared Memory (combines store data and communicate between guests)
    - Event Channels
      - Not using hardware interrupts, software/virtualized interrupts
  - How do we create a
    - Chaos tool stack talks to backend Dom0
    - Dom0 responds to chaos
    - Chaos talks to device info
- Chaos daemon replaces the tool utilities from xen
  - Tool stack optimized for para virtualized guest
- Split Tool Stack
  - VM Creation Calls - Standard Tool Stack
  - VM Creation Calls Split Tool Stack
    - Pre-create phase in the daemon

**10/22 Unikernel Lecture**

**Exokernels**

- **Monolithic OS Architecture**
  - Setup - Application (through system calls) -\&gt; kernel (which contains device drivers) -\&gt; hardware; the kernel is running in a higher privilege
  - Cons: device drivers have 90% of the bugs
- **Exokernel**
  - Setup - Application (user space)  -\&gt; library OS (user space) -\&gt; exokernel (higher privilege) - \&gt; hardware
  - **Separation of Mechanism and Policy**
    - **Mechanisms** - implementation to drive hardware or talk to network protocol
    - **Policy** - enforces access control and isolation in the application layer
    - This provides simplicity in the kernel because the kernel only implements the mechanism
  - Berkeley Packet Filter
    - Install packet handlers with specific constraints to provide safety
  - Cons:
    - Harder to provide isolation for the application
    - Harder to provide efficiency
    - Hard to scale because of writing code for device drivers
    - Device driver code has to understand user code as well as hardware since it will be running in user space in lib os, this makes them more complex
    - These cons brought about the unikernel

**Unikernels**

- The unikernel can only run one application
- It has all the libraries, dependencies, and resources to run one application
- Very hard to implement, only implemented in OCaml
  - In  Ocaml the kernel is divided into modules (one can run without the other, linux kernel everything is connected)
  - The application is implemented in  OCaml
  - At static compile time the compiler decides what modules the application needs to run and you can see all the dependencies require for the application to run
  - Then Bundles up the application and the required modules into a unikernel
  -  OCamlis a functional programming language and was built for the purpose of unikernels
- Setup - Application -\&gt; dependencies -\&gt; Unikernel; All of these run in the same privilege level (NOT on bare metal hardware)
  - So, we run the unikernel in VM and then we use the hypervisor to communicate with the hardware
  - The idea is highly tied to:
    - A modular implementation of the OS
    - Dependencies
    - A specific implementation of the application
  - Pros:
    - This provides strict application isolation because the hypervisor has hardware support to provide hardware support
    - Can be very small because you know exactly what modules you want
    - efficiency
  - Cons:
    - Must be in OCaml
    - Requires strict implementation
    - Highly tied to dependencies
    - For every change in configuration you must recompile, kill the VM, and run a new VM with the new configuration
  - LightVM is more general than the Unikernel but gives a similar performance

**Mirage OS**

- An implementation of LightVM, partial unikernel
- Same team that created Xen
- To convert an application to a unikernel model
  - Given:
    - NIC -\&gt; TCP Stack -\&gt; Linux Process
  - Create:
    - NIC \&lt;-\&gt; Shim 2 \&lt;-\&gt; OCaml TCP/IP Stack \&lt;-\&gt; Shim 1 \&lt;-\&gt; Linux Process
  - By:
    - Implementing Shim -  a translation layer, a library that transparently intercepts API calls and changes the arguments passed, handles the operation itself or redirects the operation elsewhere
      - Anything that does not have an  Ocaml implementation needs a shim
    -  OCaml TCP/IP Stack to replace TCP Stack, adds performance cost
  - Challenge is to convince the programmer to just convert to the new tool
  - So we need replace parts of the linux process with the  Ocaml stack
  - This makes it light weight and allow the programmer to see the benefits of running their project with OCaml
  - Benefits from partially using OCaml
    - Significantly higher-level language than c so we get type safety at compilation
    - Much better build system
    - Better compiler as you increase the parts that use OCaml
      -   OCaml compiles the whole OS at once which makes it a lot more efficient
      - Ex: if you never use floating point, then we never compile that when we use the OCaml compiler

**11/5 Library OS Lecture:**

**Lightweight Containers**

- Importance of lightweight containers
  - Fast deployment
  - Low resource usage
  - Low build times
- Case Study: Top 50 Docker Hub container images
  - Only 33% data was accessed by the container
  - Limitations: inefficient development and deployment of containers
- Containers are becoming heavyweight because of additional tools (not used commonly but are important)
  - Debuggers
  - Editors
  - Coreutils
  - Shell

**Cntr**

- Split Container Images
  - Original Image is split in to slim image and fat image
  - Fat container serves tools to the user and is deployed on demand
  - CNTR - provides access of the tools to the application
  - Slim Container runs the application and is the common use case
- Design Goal
  - Gerneality
    - Support a wide range of workflows (debugging, inspection, etc.)
  - Transparency
    - No modifications to OS, container engine, and application
  - Efficiency
    - No performance overhead on the application
